  <name>Sigil Auth</name>
  <summary>Hardware-backed strong authentication</summary>

  <description>
    <p>
      Sigil Auth is an open-source authentication system using hardware-bound
      cryptographic keys — no shared secrets, no passwords, no TOTP seeds.
    </p>
    <p>
      On Linux, Sigil Auth stores signing keys in a TPM 2.0 chip or a YubiKey
      with the PIV applet. Every authentication requires user presence: a PIN
      for TPM, or a PIN plus physical touch for YubiKey. Private keys never
      leave hardware.
    </p>
    <p>Features:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Push-based login approval with full action context shown before signing</li>
      <li>Multi-party approval for sensitive operations (M-of-N device quorum)</li>
      <li>Multiple server configurations in a single app</li>
      <li>Full screen-reader support via AT-SPI (Orca)</li>
      <li>Dark mode, reduced motion, and high-contrast awareness</li>
    </ul>
  </description>

